rijk","England":"England","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1492–":"about 1492–Deceased","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1518–1567":"1518–1567","1520–1567":"1520–1567","1492–Female":"1492–Deceased","about 1492":"about 1492","Abt 1518":"about 1518","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1585":"1585","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Waltham Abby, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harrison","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): from the Middle English personal name <i>Harry</i> or <i>Herry</i> + <i>-son</i>. These were the common pronunciations of <i>Henry</i> (see   Harry  ).","History: Harrison is an extremely common surname in northern England. One important and influential American family of bearers are descended from Benjamin Harrison, who emigrated from England to VA in 1633 or 1634. Descendants include another Benjamin Harrison (<i>c.</i> 1726–91), who was an activist in the American Revolution and a signer of the Declaration of Independence. His son William Henry Harrison (1773–1841) and great-grandson Benjamin Harrison (1833–1901) both became presidents of the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Harry","meanings":["English (mainly south Wales and southwestern England): from the medieval personal name <i>Harry</i>, a common form of   Henry  , with assimilation of <i>-nr-</i> to <i>-rr-</i> and regular Middle English change of <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i>. In south Wales the surname is generally a post-medieval coinage, in most cases not hereditary until the 18th or 19th century.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hariric</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>Harry</i> (see 1 above) as a surname."]},{"name":"Arrizon","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): probably an altered form of English   Harrison  ."]},{"name":"Harison","meanings":["English: variant of   Harrison  ."]},{"name":"Arrison","meanings":["English: variant of   Harrison  ."]}]},{"name":"Annis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and English: a medieval vernacular form of   Agnes  , which gave rise to a surname. Its modern use as a given name is probably at least in part a transferred use of the surname as well as a revival of the medieval given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Annice","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Annis  , based on the numerous women's names ending in <i>-ice</i>."]},{"name":"Annys","meanings":["and English: a medieval vernacular form of   Agnes  , which gave rise to a surname. Its modern use as a given name is probably at least in part a transferred use of the surname as well as a revival of the medieval given name."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":57,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":66,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":77,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":93,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":95,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Annis Harrison was born about 1492, in England. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Robert Cheney Sr.."},"et":{"about 1492–":"umbes 1492–Surnud","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1518–1567":"1518–1567","1520–1567":"1520–1567","1492–Female":"1492–Surnud","about 1492":"umbes 1492","Abt 1518":"umbes 1518","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1542":"1542","1585":"1585","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Waltham Abby, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Waltham Abbey, Essex, England":"Waltham Abbey, Essex, England"},"fi":{"about 1492–":"noin 1492–Kuollut","1490–1542":"1490–1542","1518–1567":"1518–1567","1520–1567":"1520–1567","1492–Female":"1492–Kuollut","about 1492":"noin 1492","Abt 1518":"noin 1518","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1569":"1569"